		<description>I think the point of greasemonkey (and it&#039;s power) is that it is expressly for hacking.  Real production solutions need to be architected to solve problems from the start.  Simple, last-mile type problems tho, can be handled while real patches/solutions are assembled.  Greasemonkey isn&#039;t a production solution by design.  It&#039;s a final output parser that allows for the ultimate in customization.  At it&#039;s heart, it&#039;s still screen-scraping and therefore, brittle by design.</description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I think the point of greasemonkey (and it&#8217;s power) is that it is expressly for hacking.  Real production solutions need to be architected to solve problems from the start.  Simple, last-mile type problems tho, can be handled while real patches/solutions are assembled.  Greasemonkey isn&#8217;t a production solution by design.  It&#8217;s a final output parser that allows for the ultimate in customization.  At it&#8217;s heart, it&#8217;s still screen-scraping and therefore, brittle by design.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
